Martin,

I ran a quick test, and nothing seems to be wrong with
JUnit4TestAdapter and @Test(expected).  I wonder--this small example
looks consistent with Maven entirely skipping the suite() method, and
running the class as if it were JUnit 3--since the method starts with
&quot;test&quot;, it would still get picked up and run.  Are you sure Maven is
using the result of the suite() method?  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 12/21/06, martin.burger &lt;mburger@...-sb.de&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hello!
&gt;
&gt; I try to run a Junit 4 test case with Maven 2. Maven 2 does not
&gt; support Junit 4, so I added the following method to my test case:
&gt;
&gt;     public static junit.framework.Test suite() {
&gt;         return new JUnit4TestAdapter(MyTest.class);
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; Now, Maven can run that test case.
&gt;
&gt; But there is a problem: I defined a test method that expects an exception:
&gt;
&gt;     @Test(expected = IllegalArgumentException.class)
&gt;     public void testNullArgument() {
&gt;         new SomeClass(null);
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; If I run that test in Eclipse 3.2 (has support for Junit 4), I will
&gt; get green lights.
&gt;
&gt; But Maven fails:
&gt;
&gt; Test set: MyTest
&gt; -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
&gt; Tests run: 9, Failures: 1, Errors: 0, Skipped: 0, Time elapsed: 0.023
&gt; sec &lt;&lt;&lt; FAILURE!
&gt; MyTest.testNullArgument()  Time elapsed: 0.001 sec  &lt;&lt;&lt; FAILURE!
&gt; java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Given arg must not be null.
&gt;         at org.apache.commons.lang.Validate.notNull(Validate.java:201)
&gt;         at SomeClass.&lt;init&gt;(SomeClass.java:51)
&gt;         at MyTest.testNullArgument(MyTest.java:27)
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Finally, my question: does the JUnit4TestAdapter support expected
&gt; exceptions?
&gt;
&gt; Regards, Martin Burger
